4 Combinatorial reformulation
We interpret the problem as a constrained path in a layered state space.
Each state corresponds to:
• a subset U ⊆{1,...,n}of used elements,
• a current sum s= i∈U i,
with transitions:
(U,s) →(U ∪{x},s+ x)
for x / ∈U, provided s+ x is not a perfect square.
Thus, valid permutations correspond to Hamiltonian paths in a directed acyclic state graph.
5 Dynamic programming algorithm
We define a DP over subsets:
DP[mask][s] = number of ways to reach state (mask,s).
Where: - mask encodes used elements, - s is the current prefix sum.
Transition:
DP[mask∪{x}][s+ x]+ = DP[mask][s]
if s+ x is not a perfect square.
